      <h2>Are Gummy Vitamins Effective? — FAQ</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummy vitamins as effective as pill vitamins?</summary><p>For most nutrients, yes. Clinical studies show equivalent bioavailability for vitamins D, C, B12, melatonin, and others when doses are equivalent. The key is ensuring your gummy contains an adequate dose of the active ingredient.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy vitamins have enough nutrients?</summary><p>It varies by nutrient. Gummies deliver clinically effective doses for vitamins D, B12, biotin, and melatonin. However, minerals requiring large doses (calcium, iron) are difficult to fit into gummy form at therapeutic levels.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can you absorb vitamins from gummies?</summary><p>Yes. Chewing begins digestion in the mouth, and some nutrients (melatonin, B12) benefit from sublingual absorption during chewing. Studies show equivalent or slightly superior absorption for several nutrients in gummy form.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why do some doctors not recommend gummy vitamins?</summary><p>Concerns include sugar content, lower nutrient density than tablets, and a 2017 report showing high failure rates in quality testing. The industry has improved significantly since then. Choose USP or NSF-certified brands for reliable quality.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy vitamins lose potency over time?</summary><p>Yes, faster than tablets. Moisture accelerates degradation of vitamin C, B-vitamins, and probiotics. Gummies may lose 20-30% of vitamin C within 12 months. Buy from high-turnover retailers and check expiration dates.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are the disadvantages of gummy vitamins?</summary><p>Sugar content (2-4g/serving), lower nutrient density, shorter shelf life, higher cost (2-5x more than pills), overconsumption risk (candy-like taste), and limited mineral delivery (calcium, iron hard to dose adequately).</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummy vitamins good for adults?</summary><p>Yes. The compliance advantage is significant — adults are 30-40% more likely to take gummies daily versus pills. For the 40% of adults who struggle with pill swallowing, gummies remove a major barrier to consistent supplementation.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take gummy or regular vitamins?</summary><p>Choose gummies for nutrients that work well in gummy form (D3, B12, melatonin, biotin) and if compliance is an issue. Choose pills for high-dose nutrients (iron, calcium, omega-3) or if budget is the priority. Many people use both formats.</p></details>
    </section>

